  "stage": {
    "id": "architecture_components",
    "stageNumber": 3,
    "title": "Architecture Components",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "positional_encoding",
        "title": "Positional Encoding",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Sinusoidal position signals\n- Relative position learning\n- No sequential bottleneck\n\nSince the Transformer processes all positions in parallel with no recurrence, it has no inherent sense of word order. 'Dog bites man' and 'Man bites dog' would look identical! Positional encodings solve this.\n\nVaswani et al. use sinusoidal functions:\nPE(pos,2i) = sin(pos/10000^(2i/d_model))\nPE(pos,2i+1) = cos(pos/10000^(2i/d_model))\n\nThink of it as giving each position a unique fingerprint using waves of different frequencies. The clever choice of sinusoids allows the model to learn relative positions, since PE(pos+k) can be represented as a linear function of PE(pos).\n\nThese encodings are added directly to the input embeddings, injecting position information that flows through the entire network.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "feed_forward_network",
        "title": "Position-wise Feed-Forward Network",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Two linear layers with ReLU\n- Applied position-wise\n- d_ff=2048, d_model=512\n\nEach layer in the Transformer contains not just attention, but also a position-wise feed-forward network. It's applied identically to each position:\n\nFFN(x) = max(0, xW₁ + b₁)W₂ + b₂\n\nThe inner layer expands to d_ff=2048 dimensions (4x the model dimension of 512), applies ReLU, then projects back down. Think of it as each position having its own little two-layer neural network to process the attended information.\n\nWhile attention mixes information across positions, the FFN processes each position's representation independently—a powerful combination of global mixing and local processing.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "masked_attention",
        "title": "Masked Self-Attention",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Future position masking\n- Auto-regressive constraint\n- Training parallelization\n\nIn the decoder, we need to preserve the auto-regressive property: when predicting position i, we can only use information from positions less than i. But self-attention naturally attends to all positions!\n\nThe solution is masking: before softmax, we set attention scores for illegal connections (future positions) to -∞. After softmax, these become zero—no information leaks from the future.\n\nThink of it as covering answers on a test while working through problems one by one. During training, this masking lets us process the entire sequence in parallel while enforcing the constraint that would exist during actual generation.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "encoder_decoder_attention",
        "title": "Encoder-Decoder Attention",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Cross-attention between encoder/decoder\n- Queries from decoder, K/V from encoder\n- Global input context for generation\n\nThe encoder-decoder attention layer is how the decoder accesses information from the input sequence. Queries come from the previous decoder layer, while keys and values come from the encoder output.\n\nThis is like a translator looking back at the source text while writing: 'What part of the English sentence should I focus on to produce this French word?' The decoder asks questions (queries), and the encoder's representation provides the answers (keys and values).\n\nEvery decoder layer has this cross-attention, allowing each generated token to attend to all input positions with a fresh perspective.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "encoder_stack",
        "title": "Transformer Encoder",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- N=6 identical layers\n- Self-attention + FFN per layer\n- Residual connections + LayerNorm\n\nThe Transformer encoder consists of N=6 identical layers stacked on top of each other. Each layer has two sub-layers:\n\n1. Multi-head self-attention\n2. Position-wise feed-forward network\n\nBoth are wrapped with residual connections and layer normalization: LayerNorm(x + Sublayer(x)).\n\nThink of it as passing a document through 6 rounds of review, where each round both considers the global context (attention) and refines local understanding (FFN). The output is a rich, contextual representation of every input position.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "decoder_stack",
        "title": "Transformer Decoder",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Masked self-attention\n- Encoder-decoder cross-attention\n- Auto-regressive generation\n\nThe decoder is similar to the encoder but with a crucial addition. Each of its N=6 layers has three sub-layers:\n\n1. Masked multi-head self-attention (can't peek at future)\n2. Multi-head encoder-decoder attention (looks at input)\n3. Position-wise feed-forward network\n\nAll wrapped with residual connections and layer normalization.\n\nThe decoder builds the output sequence token by token. At each step, it considers what it's generated so far (masked self-attention), consults the input (encoder-decoder attention), then processes this information (FFN) to predict the next token.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-3",
      "question": "How many sub-layers does each decoder layer have? Answer with a number.",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "2 (masked attention + FFN)",
        "3 (masked attention + encoder-decoder attention + FFN)",
        "4 (two attention layers + two FFN layers)"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "3 (masked attention + encoder-decoder attention + FFN)",
      "position": {
        "x": 18,
        "y": 7
      }
    },
